</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company and UPM-Kymmene Corporation (&#8220;UPM&#8221;), a Finnish paper manufacturing company, are partners through subsidiary companies in Madison. The Company&#8217;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	40%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;ownership of Madison is through an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	80%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	-owned consolidated subsidiary that owns
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	50%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of Madison. UPM owns
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	60%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of Madison, including a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	10%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;interest through a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	20%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;noncontrolling interest in the consolidated subsidiary of the Company. In March 2016, UPM announced the closure of the paper mill, which occurred in May 2016. During the first quarter of 2016, we recognized
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$41.4 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in losses from joint ventures related to the announced closure of the paper mill. Our proportionate share of the loss is reduced by the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	20%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;noncontrolling interest. As a result of the mill closure, we wrote our investment down to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	zero
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and recorded a liability of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$28.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, reflecting our share of the impairment and losses incurred in 2016 by Madison and our funding obligation. These amounts are presented in &#8220;Accrued expenses and other&#8221; in our Consolidated Balance Sheets.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company&#8217;s joint venture in Madison is currently being liquidated and a plan is in place to sell assets (including hydro power assets) at the mill site. In the fourth quarter of 2016, Madison sold its non-hydro power assets at the mill site and we recognized a gain of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.9 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;related to the sale. We expect the sale of the hydro power assets to be completed in early 2017. We believe the proceeds from the sale will be more than sufficient to cover Madison&#8217;s obligations and therefore allow us to reverse our liability.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We received
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	no
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;distributions from Madison in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, or
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We have a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	49%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;equity interest in a Canadian newsprint company, Malbaie. The other
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	51%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;is owned by Resolute FP Canada Inc., a subsidiary of Resolute Forest Products Inc. (&#8220;Resolute&#8221;), a Delaware corporation. Resolute is a large global manufacturer of paper, market pulp and wood products. Malbaie manufactures newsprint on the paper machine it owns within Resolute&#8217;s paper mill in Clermont, Quebec. Malbaie is wholly dependent upon Resolute for its pulp, which is purchased by Malbaie from Resolute&#8217;s Clermont paper mill.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We purchase newsprint from Malbaie, and previously purchased supercalendered paper from Madison, at competitive prices. Such purchases totaled approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$14 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$12 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$20 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We received
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	no
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;distributions from Malbaie in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.9 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Cost Method Investments
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

	The aggregate carrying amount of cost method investments included in &#8220;Miscellaneous assets&#8217;&#8217; in our Consolidated Balance Sheets were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	6.625% Notes
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In November 2010, we issued
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$225.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;aggregate principal amount of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	6.625%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;senior unsecured notes due December&#160;15, 2016 (&#8220;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	6.625%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;Notes&#8221;). During 2014, we repurchased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$18.4 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;principal amount of the 6.625% Notes and recorded a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$2.2 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;pre-tax charge in connection with the repurchases. In December 2016, the Company repaid, at maturity, the remaining principal amount of the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	6.625%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;Notes.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Sale-Leaseback Financing
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In March 2009, we entered into an agreement to sell and simultaneously lease back a portion of our leasehold condominium interest in our Company&#8217;s headquarters building located at 620 Eighth Avenue in New York City (the &#8220;Condo Interest&#8221;).&#160;The sale price for the Condo Interest was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$225.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;less transaction costs, for net proceeds of approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$211 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The lease term is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	15
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;years, and we have
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;renewal options that could extend the term for an additional
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	20
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;years. We have an option, exercisable in 2019, to repurchase the Condo Interest for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$250.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, which we currently expect to exercise.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The transaction is accounted for as a financing transaction. As such, we have continued to depreciate the Condo Interest and account for the rental payments as interest expense. The difference between the purchase option price of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$250.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and the net sale proceeds of approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$211 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, or approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$39 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, is being amortized over a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	-year period through interest expense. The effective interest rate on this transaction was approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	13%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>

</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	8. Fair Value Measurements
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Fair value is the price that would be received upon the sale of an asset or paid upon transfer of a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. The transaction would be in the principal or most advantageous market for the asset or liability, based on assumptions that a market participant would use in pricing the asset or liability. The fair value hierarchy consists of three levels:
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Level 1&#8211;quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities that the reporting entity has the ability to access at the measurement date;
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Level 2&#8211;inputs other than quoted prices included within Level 1 that are observable for the asset or liability, either directly or indirectly; and
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Level 3&#8211;unobservable inputs for the asset or liability.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Assets/Liabilities Measured and Recorded at Fair Value on a Recurring Basis
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	As of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;25, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;27, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, we had assets related to our qualified pension plans measured at fair value. The required disclosures regarding such assets are presented in Note 9.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The deferred compensation liability, included in &#8220;Other liabilities&#8212;Other&#8221; in our Consolidated Balance Sheets, consists of deferrals under The New York Times Company Deferred Executive Compensation Plan (the &#8220;DEC&#8221;), which enables certain eligible executives to elect to defer a portion of their compensation on a pre-tax basis. The deferred amounts are invested at the executives&#8217; option in various mutual funds. The fair value of deferred compensation is based on the mutual fund investments elected by the executives and on quoted prices in active markets for identical assets. Participation in the DEC was frozen effective December 31, 2015, and no new contributions may be made into the plan.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Assets Measured and Recorded at Fair Value on a Non-Recurring Basis
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Certain non-financial assets, such as goodwill, other intangible assets, property, plant and equipment and certain investments are only recorded at fair value if an impairment charge is recognized. Goodwill and intangible assets are initially recorded at fair value in purchase accounting. We classified all of these measurements as Level 3, as we used unobservable inputs within the valuation methodologies that were significant to the fair value measurements, and the valuations required management&#8216;s judgment due to the absence of quoted market prices. The following tables present non-financial assets that were measured and recorded at fair value on a non-recurring basis and the total impairment losses recorded in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;on those assets. There was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	no
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;material impairment recognized in 2016 and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.

<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;BORDER-TOP:1PX SOLID #000000;">

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	9,216
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;BORDER-TOP:1PX SOLID #000000;">

<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;BORDER-TOP:1PX SOLID #000000;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

	(1)

	&#160;

<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:24PX;">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;PADDING-LEFT:0PX;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(1)
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Impairment losses related to Madison are included within &#8220;Loss from joint ventures&#8221; for the year ended December&#160;28, 2014. See Note 5 for additional information.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:30PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The impairment of assets in 2014 reflects the impairment of one of our investments in joint ventures, Madison. During the fourth quarter of 2014, we estimated the fair value less cost to sell of the group held for sale, using unobservable inputs (Level 3). We recorded a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$9.2 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;non-cash charge in the fourth quarter of 2014. Our proportionate share of the loss was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$4.7 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;after tax and adjusted for the allocation of the loss to the non-controlling interest.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Financial Instruments Disclosed, But Not Reported, at Fair Value
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Our marketable securities, which include U.S. Treasury securities, corporate debt securities, U.S. government agency securities, municipal securities, certificates of deposit and commercial paper, are recorded at amortized cost (see Note 3). As of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;25, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;27, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the amortized cost approximated fair value because of the short-term maturity and highly liquid nature of these investments. We classified these investments as Level 2 since the fair value estimates are based on market observable inputs for investments with similar terms and maturities.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The carrying value of our long-term debt was approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$240 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;25, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$236 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;27, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The fair value of our long-term debt was approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$298 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;25, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$316 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;27, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. We estimate the fair value of our debt utilizing market quotations for debt that have quoted prices in active markets. Since our debt does not trade on a daily basis in an active market, the fair value estimates are based on market observable inputs based on borrowing rates currently available for debt with similar terms and average maturities (Level 2).
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<A NAME="A2016FORM10-K_Q4PROJECT_HTM_SC4DB157B478F54B89A201039413475A0">
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	9. Pension Benefits
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Single-Employer Plans
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We sponsor several single-employer defined benefit pension plans, the majority of which have been frozen. We also participate in two joint Company and Guild-sponsored plans covering employees who are members of The News Guild of New York, including The Newspaper Guild of New York - The New York Times Pension Fund, which was frozen in 2012, and replaced by The Guild-Times Adjustable Pension Plan.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We also have a foreign-based pension plan for certain employees (the &#8220;foreign plan&#8221;). The information for the foreign plan is combined with the information for U.S. non-qualified plans. The benefit obligation of the foreign plan is immaterial to our total benefit obligation.
</FONT>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	As part of our strategy to reduce the size and volatility of our pension obligations, we have offered lump-sum payments to certain former employees participating in both our qualified and non-qualified pension plans. In the fourth quarter of 2016, we recorded a pension settlement charge of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$21.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in connection with a lump-sum payment offer made to certain former employees who participated in certain qualified pension plans. These lump-sum payments totaled
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$49.5 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and were made with cash from the qualified pension plans, not with Company cash. The effect of this lump-sum payment offer was to reduce our pension obligations by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$52.2 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. In addition, we recorded a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.6 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;curtailment related to the streamlining of the Company&#8217;s international print operations. See Note 7 for more information on the streamlining of the Company&#8217;s international print operations.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In the first quarter of 2015, we recorded a pension settlement charge of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$40.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in connection with a lump-sum payment offer made to certain former employees who participated in certain qualified pension plans. These lump-sum payments totaled
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$98.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and were made with cash from the qualified pension plans, not with Company cash. The effect of this lump-sum payment offer was to reduce our pension obligations by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$142.8 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In the second quarter of 2014, we recorded a pension settlement charge of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$9.5 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in connection with a lump-sum payment offer made to certain former employees who participated in certain non-qualified pension plans.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	These lump-sum payments totaled
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$24.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and were paid out of Company cash. The effect of this lump-sum payment offer was to reduce our pension obligations by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$32.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

	, respectively.

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In the fourth quarter of 2015, the Company&#8217;s ERISA Management Committee made a decision to freeze the accrual of benefits under the Retirement Annuity Plan For Craft Employees of The New York Times Companies with respect to all participants covered by a collective bargaining agreement between the Company and The New York Newspaper Printing Pressmen&#8217;s Union No. 2N/1SE, effective as of the close of business on December 31, 2015. As a result, we recorded a curtailment of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in 2015.
</FONT>
</DIV>

</FONT>

	&#32;for
</FONT>

<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;BORDER-TOP:1PX SOLID #000000;">

</FONT>

<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

</FONT>
</DIV>

<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	2.50
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">

	%
</FONT>
</DIV>

</TABLE>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We determined our discount rate using a Ryan ALM, Inc. Curve (the &#8220;Ryan Curve&#8221;). The Ryan Curve provides the bonds included in the curve and allows adjustments for certain outliers (i.e., bonds on &#8220;watch&#8221;). We believe the Ryan Curve allows us to calculate an appropriate discount rate.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	To determine our discount rate, we project a cash flow based on annual accrued benefits. The projected&#160;plan cash flow is discounted to the measurement date, which is the last day of our fiscal year, using the annual spot&#160;rates provided in the Ryan Curve.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In determining the expected long-term rate of return on assets, we evaluated input from our investment consultants, actuaries and investment management firms, including our review of asset class return expectations, as well as long-term historical asset class returns. Projected returns by such consultants and economists are based on broad equity and bond indices. Our objective is to select an average rate of earnings expected on existing plan assets and expected contributions to the plan during the year, less expense expected to be incurred by the plan during the year.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The market-related value of plan assets is multiplied by the expected long-term rate of return on assets to compute the expected return on plan assets, a component of net periodic pension cost. The market-related value of plan assets is a calculated value that recognizes changes in fair value over
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;years.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In October 2014, the Society of Actuaries (&#8220;SOA&#8221;) released new mortality tables that increased life expectancy assumptions. During the fourth quarter of 2014, we adopted the new mortality tables and revised the mortality assumptions used in determining our pension and postretirement benefit obligations. The net impact to our qualified and non-qualified pension obligations resulting from the new mortality assumptions in 2014 was an increase of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$117.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In October 2016, the SOA released new mortality tables that decreased life expectancy assumptions. During the fourth quarter of 2016, we adopted the new mortality tables and revised the mortality assumptions used in determining our pension and postretirement benefit obligations. The net impact to our qualified and non-qualified pension obligations resulting from the new mortality assumptions in 2016 was a decrease of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$34.7 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	For fiscal year 2016, we changed the approach used to calculate the service and interest components of net periodic benefit cost for benefit plans to provide a more precise measurement of service and interest costs. Historically, we calculated these service and interest components utilizing a single weighted-average discount rate derived from the yield curve used to measure the benefit obligation at the beginning of the period. We elected to utilize an approach that discounts the individual expected cash flows using the applicable spot rates derived from the yield curve over the projected cash flow period. The spot rates used to determine service and interest costs ranged from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	1.32%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	4.79%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. Service costs and interest costs for our pension plans were reduced by approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$18 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;due to the change in methodology.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Plan Assets
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;PADDING-LEFT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Company-Sponsored Pension Plans
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The assets underlying the Company-sponsored qualified pension plans are managed by professional investment managers. These investment managers are selected and monitored by the pension investment committee, composed of certain senior executives, who are appointed by the Finance Committee of the Board of Directors of the Company. The Finance Committee is responsible for adopting our investment policy, which includes rules regarding the selection and retention of qualified advisors and investment managers. The pension investment committee is responsible for implementing and monitoring compliance with our investment policy, selecting and monitoring
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<BR>
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	P.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	78
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;&#8211; THE NEW YORK TIMES COMPANY
</FONT>
</DIV>

<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
<A NAME="eolPage81"></A>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	investment managers and communicating the investment guidelines and performance objectives to the investment managers.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Our contributions are made on a basis determined by the actuaries in accordance with the funding requirements and limitations of the Employee Retirement Income Security Act (&#8220;ERISA&#8221;) and the Internal Revenue Code.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Investment Policy and Strategy
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The primary long-term investment objective is to allocate assets in a manner that produces a total rate of return that meets or exceeds the growth of our pension liabilities. Our investment objective is to transition the asset mix to hedge liabilities and minimize volatility in the funded status of the plans.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;PADDING-LEFT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Asset Allocation Guidelines
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In accordance with our asset allocation strategy, for substantially all of our Company-sponsored pension plan assets, investments are categorized into long duration fixed income investments whose value is highly correlated to that of the pension plan obligations (&#8220;Long Duration Assets&#8221;) or other investments, such as equities and high-yield fixed income securities, whose return over time is expected to exceed the rate of growth in our pension plan obligations (&#8220;Return-Seeking Assets&#8221;).
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The proportional allocation of assets between Long Duration Assets and Return-Seeking Assets is dependent on the funded status of each pension plan. Under our policy, for example, a funded status between
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	95%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	97.5%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;requires an allocation of total assets of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	53%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	63%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;to Long Duration Assets and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	37%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	47%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;to Return-Seeking Assets. As a plan's funded status increases, the allocation to Long Duration Assets will increase and the allocation to Return-Seeking Assets will decrease.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The following asset allocation guidelines apply to the Return-Seeking Assets:
</FONT>
</DIV>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_46"></A>

<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Asset Category

</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">

</TD>
<TD COLSPAN="4" STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">

	Percentage Range

</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	Public Equity
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#ACACAC;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="OVERFLOW:HIDDEN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#160;

<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:24PX;">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;PADDING-LEFT:0PX;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(4)
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Certain investments that are measured at fair value using the NAV per share (or its equivalent) have not been classified in the fair value hierarchy.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;PADDING-LEFT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Level 1 and Level 2 Investments
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Where quoted prices are available in an active market for identical assets, such as equity securities traded on an exchange, transactions for the asset occur with such frequency that the pricing information is available on an ongoing/daily basis. We classify these types of investments as Level 1 where the fair value represents the closing/last trade price for these particular securities.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	For our investments where pricing data may not be readily available, fair values are estimated by using quoted prices for similar assets, in both active and not active markets, and observable inputs, other than quoted prices, such as interest rates and credit risk. We classify these types of investments as Level 2 because we are able to reasonably estimate the fair value through inputs that are observable, either directly or indirectly. There are no restrictions on our ability to sell any of our Level 1 and Level 2 investments.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>

	In August 2014, the Highway and Transportation Funding Act of 2014 was enacted. The legislation extended interest rate stabilization for single-employer defined benefit pension plan funding for an additional five years. In
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$7.8 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. We expect contributions to total approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

</FONT>

</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:24PX;">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:8PT;PADDING-LEFT:0PX;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(1)
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	While benefit payments under these plans are expected to continue beyond 2026, we have presented in this table only those benefit payments estimated over the next 10 years.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Multiemployer Plans
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We contribute to a number of multiemployer defined benefit pension plans under the terms of various collective bargaining agreements that cover our union-represented employees. In recent years, certain events, such as amendments to various collective bargaining agreements and the sale of the New England Media Group, resulted in withdrawals from multiemployer pension plans. These actions, along with a reduction in covered employees, have resulted in us estimating withdrawal liabilities to the respective plans for our proportionate share of any unfunded vested benefits. In 2016 and 2015, we recorded
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$6.7 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#FF0000;">
	&#32;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$9.1 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in charges for partial withdrawal obligations under multiemployer pension plans, respectively. There was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	no
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;such charge in 2014.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Our multiemployer pension plan withdrawal liability was approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$113 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;25, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$124 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;27, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The decrease was due to the settlement of various withdrawal liabilities in 2016. This liability represents the present value of the obligations related to complete and partial withdrawals that have already occurred as well as an estimate of future partial withdrawals that we considered probable and reasonably estimable. For those plans that have yet to provide us with a demand letter, the actual liability will not be fully known until they complete a final assessment of the withdrawal liability and issue a demand to us. Therefore, the estimate of our multiemployer pension plan liability will be adjusted as more information becomes available that allows us to refine our estimates.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The risks of participating in multiemployer plans are different from single-employer plans in the following aspects:
</FONT>
</DIV>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:48PX;">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;PADDING-LEFT:24PX;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#8226;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Assets contributed to the multiemployer plan by one employer may be used to provide benefits to employees of other participating employers.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:48PX;">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;PADDING-LEFT:24PX;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#8226;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	If a participating employer stops contributing to the plan, the unfunded obligations of the plan may be borne by the remaining participating employers.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:48PX;">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;PADDING-LEFT:24PX;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#8226;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	If we elect to withdraw from these plans or if we trigger a partial withdrawal due to declines in contribution base units or a partial cessation of our obligation to contribute, we may be assessed a withdrawal liability based on a calculated share of the underfunded status of the plan.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

<TD STYLE="WIDTH:48PX;">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;PADDING-LEFT:24PX;">

	&#8226;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	If a multiemployer plan from which we have withdrawn subsequently experiences a mass withdrawal, we may be required to make additional contributions under applicable law.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>

<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
<A NAME="eolPage85"></A>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Our participation in significant plans for the fiscal period ended
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;25, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, is outlined in the table below. The &#8220;EIN/Pension Plan Number&#8221; column provides the Employer Identification Number (&#8220;EIN&#8221;) and the three-digit plan number. The zone status is based on the latest information that we received from the plan and is certified by the plan&#8217;s actuary. A plan is generally classified in critical status if a funding deficiency is projected&#160;within four years&#160;or five years.&#160; A plan in critical status is classified in critical and declining status if it is projected to become insolvent in the next 15 or 20 years, depending on other criteria. A plan is classified in endangered status if its funded percentage is less than 80% or a funding deficiency is projected&#160;within seven years. If the plan satisfies both of these triggers, it is classified in seriously endangered status. A plan not classified in any other status is classified in the green zone. The &#8220;FIP/RP Status Pending/Implemented&#8221; column indicates plans for which a financial improvement plan (&#8220;FIP&#8221;) or a rehabilitation plan (&#8220;RP&#8221;) is either pending or has been implemented. The &#8220;Surcharge Imposed&#8221; column includes plans in a red zone status that are required to pay a surcharge in excess of regular contributions. The last column lists the expiration date(s) of the collective bargaining agreement(s) to which the plans are subject.
</FONT>
</DIV>

<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	Paper-Handlers&#8217;-Publishers&#8217; Pension Fund
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	3/31/2016 &amp; 3/31/2015
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(1) Forms 5500 for the plans&#8217; year ended of 12/31/16 and 5/31/16 were not available as of the date we filed our financial statements.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company received a notice and demand for payment of withdrawal liability from the Newspaper and Mail Deliverers&#8217;-Publishers&#8217; Pension Fund in September 2013 and December 2014 associated with partial withdrawals. See Note 18 for further information.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<A NAME="A2016FORM10-K_Q4PROJECT_HTM_S656D6644560051CFBD3FF54CC190761B">
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	10. Other Postretirement Benefits
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We provide health benefits to retired employees (and their eligible dependents) who meet the definition of an eligible participant and certain age and service requirements, as outlined in the plan document. While we offer pre-age
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	65
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;retiree medical coverage to employees who meet certain retiree medical eligibility requirements, we do not provide post-age
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	65
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;retiree medical benefits for employees who retired on or after March&#160;1, 2009. We also contribute to a postretirement plan for Guild employees of The New York Times under the provisions of a collective bargaining agreement. We accrue the costs of postretirement benefits during the employees&#8217; active years of service and our policy is to pay our portion of insurance premiums and claims from our assets.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Net Periodic Other Postretirement Benefit (Income)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	/
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Expense
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The components of net periodic postretirement benefit (income)/expense were as follows:
</FONT>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:48PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In September 2014 and December 2014, the ERISA Management Committee approved certain changes to The New York Times Company Retiree Medical Plan provisions, which triggered a remeasurement under ASC 715-60, &#8220;Compensation &#8212; Retirement Benefits &#8212; Defined Benefit Plans &#8212; Other Postretirement.&#8221; The changes in the plan provisions decreased obligations by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$25.5 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and the change in discount rate as of the remeasurement date increased obligations by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.6 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. Overall, the remeasurement decreased our obligations by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$21.9 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as reflected in other comprehensive income in our Consolidated Balance Sheets and Consolidated Statements of Comprehensive Income/(Loss).
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>

	The estimated actuarial loss and prior service credit that will be amortized from accumulated other comprehensive loss into net periodic benefit cost over the next fiscal year is approximately

</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In connection with collective bargaining agreements, we contribute to several multiemployer welfare plans. These plans provide medical benefits to active and retired employees covered under the respective collective bargaining agreement. Contributions are made in accordance with the formula in the relevant agreement. Postretirement costs related to these plans are not reflected above and were approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$15 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$16 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$18 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	While benefit payments under these plans are expected to continue beyond 2026, we have presented in this table only those benefit payments estimated over the next 10 years.
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	We accrue the cost of certain benefits provided to former or inactive employees after employment, but before retirement. The cost is recognized only when it is probable and can be estimated. Benefits include life insurance, disability benefits and health-care continuation coverage. The accrued obligation for these benefits amounted to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$11.4 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;25, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$12.9 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;27, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In October 2014, the SOA released new mortality tables that increased life expectancy assumptions. During the fourth quarter of 2014, we adopted the new mortality tables and revised the mortality assumptions used in determining our pension and postretirement benefit obligations. The net impact to our postretirement obligations resulting from the new mortality assumptions was an increase of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$4.2 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<BR>
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	THE NEW YORK TIMES COMPANY &#8211; P.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	87
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
<A NAME="eolPage90"></A>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In October 2016, the SOA released new mortality tables that decreased life expectancy assumptions. During the fourth quarter of 2016, we adopted the new mortality tables and revised the mortality assumptions used in determining our pension and postretirement benefit obligations. The net impact to our qualified and non-qualified pension obligations resulting from the new mortality assumptions in 2016 was a decrease of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.2 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	For fiscal year 2016, we changed the approach used to calculate the service and interest components of net periodic benefit cost for benefit plans to provide a more precise measurement of service and interest costs. Historically, we calculated these service and interest components utilizing a single weighted-average discount rate derived from the yield curve used to measure the benefit obligation at the beginning of the period. We have elected to utilize an approach that discounts the individual expected cash flows using the applicable spot rates derived from the yield curve over the projected cash flow period. The spot rates used to determine service and interest costs ranged from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	1.32%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	4.79%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. Service costs and interest costs for our postretirement plans were reduced by approximately $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	1 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;due to the change in methodology.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<A NAME="A2016FORM10-K_Q4PROJECT_HTM_S24B009A1776957CFA828CEC2387C4AB7">
</A>
</DIV>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	11. Other Liabilities
</FONT>
</DIV>

	We invest deferred compensation in life insurance products designed to closely mirror the performance of the investment funds that the participants select. Our investments in life insurance products are included in &#8220;Miscellaneous assets&#8221; in our Consolidated Balance Sheets, and were
</FONT>

	&#32;and

	$71.9 million

	&#32;as of

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;We assess&#160;whether a valuation allowance should be established against deferred tax assets based on the consideration of both positive and negative evidence using a &#8220;more likely than not&#8221; standard. In making such judgments, significant weight is given to evidence that can be objectively verified. We evaluated our deferred tax assets for recoverability using a consistent approach that considers our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	-year historical cumulative income/(loss), including an assessment of the degree to which any such losses were due to items that are unusual in nature (i.e., impairments of nondeductible goodwill and intangible assets).
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	As of December 27, 2015, we had a full valuation allowance on net operating losses of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$36.2 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;associated with non-U.S. operations, as we determined those losses were not realizable on a more-likely-than-not basis. &#160;As of December 25, 2016, following&#160;the streamlining of the Company's international print operations, those net operating losses were no longer available for use and accordingly both the net operating losses and the associated full valuation allowance have been removed from the Consolidated Balance Sheets.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

	&#32;income tax benefit, respectively, primarily due to a reduction in the Company&#8217;s reserve for uncertain tax positions.

Management believes that our accrual for tax liabilities is adequate for all open audit years. This assessment relies on estimates and assumptions and may involve a series of complex judgments about future events.

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	13. Discontinued Operations
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	New England Media Group
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In the fourth quarter of 2013, we completed the sale of substantially all of the assets and operating liabilities of the New England Media Group &#8212; consisting of The Boston Globe, BostonGlobe.com, Boston.com, the T&amp;G, Telegram.com and related properties &#8212; and our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	49%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;equity interest in Metro Boston, for approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$70.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in cash, subject to customary adjustments. The net after-tax proceeds from the sale, including a tax benefit, were approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$74.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. In 2013, we recognized a pre-tax gain of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$47.6 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;on the sale (
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$28.1 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;after tax), which was almost entirely comprised of a curtailment gain. This curtailment gain was primarily related to an acceleration of prior service credits from retiree medical plan amendments announced in prior years, and was due to a cessation of service for employees at the New England Media Group. Post-closing adjustments in 2014 resulted in a loss of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$0.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. In the fourth quarter of 2016, we recorded a charge of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.7 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;(
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$2.3 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;after tax) in connection with the settlement of litigation involving NEMG T&amp;G, Inc., a subsidiary of the Company that was part of the New England Media Group. The results of operations of the New England Media Group have been classified as discontinued operations for all periods presented.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	About Group
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In the fourth quarter of 2012, we completed the sale of the About Group, consisting of About.com, ConsumerSearch.com, CalorieCount.com and related businesses, to IAC/InterActiveCorp. for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$300.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in cash, plus a net working capital adjustment of approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$17.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The sale resulted in a pre-tax gain of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$96.7 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;(
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$61.9 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;after tax) in 2012. The net after-tax proceeds from the sale were approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$291.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. In the fourth quarter of 2014, there was a legal settlement that resulted in a loss of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$0.2 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The results of operations
</FONT>
</DIV>

	of the About Group, which had previously been presented as a reportable segment, have been classified as discontinued operations for 2014.

</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:HELVETICA,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Regional Media Group
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In the first quarter of 2012, we completed the sale of the Regional Media Group, consisting of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	16
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;regional newspapers, other print publications and related businesses, to Halifax Media Holdings LLC for approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$140.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in cash. The net after-tax proceeds from the sale, including a tax benefit, were approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$150.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The sale resulted in an after-tax gain of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$23.6 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;(including post-closing adjustments recorded in the second and fourth quarters of 2012 totaling
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$6.6 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	). In the fourth quarter of 2014, there was an environmental contingency that resulted in a loss of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$0.4 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The results of operations for the Regional Media Group have been classified as discontinued operations for 2014.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-BOTTOM:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;PADDING-LEFT:0PX;TEXT-INDENT:36PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:PALATINO,SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The results of operations for the New England Media Group, About Group and the Regional Media Group presented as discontinued operations are summarized below for 2016 and 2014. There were no discontinued operations in 2015.
</FONT>
